Put the @quinoa{1/4%cup} in a large #pot{} of water together with the @vegetable stock pot{1/2}, bring to the boil and cook for ~{20%minutes}. Drain well and put the quinoa back in the pot, covered with a #tea towel{}.

> If you have a fine enough sieve, you can rinse the quinoa before putting in the water. This will enhance the flavour.

Boil another @water{150%ml} with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. In a #bowl{}, pour this water onto the @wholewheat couscous{1/3%cup} and cover tightly. Leave for at least ~{10%mins} while you prepare the rest of the meal.

Mix together @olive oil{1%tbsp} with the @sumac{1%tsp}. Grate a pinch of the @lemon{1/2}(zested) into the oil and mix together.

Cut the @halloumi{1} into slices just under 1cm thick. Rub them all over with the sumac flavoured oil and leave to marinate while you chop your vegetables.

Turn your #grill{} to high. Finely chop the fresh @mint{2%sprigs}(finely chopped) and @flat leaf parsley{3%sprigs}(finely chopped). Chop the @cherry tomatoes{1}(quartered) into quarters. Very finely slice the @spring onion{1.5}(sliced into discs, white and green parts separated) into discs.

Place the halloumi slices on a #baking tray{}. Place under the grill and cook until the tops blister slightly.

> You want to thoroughly brown the halloumi off, but don't overcook it as it will become dry.

Stir up the quinoa and couscous with a #fork{} to separate the grains. Mix them together with 1 tsp of the whites of the spring onion. Now toss in the tomatoes and the fresh herbs.

Serve with the halloumi slices and lemon wedges to squeeze over the top. Lastly, scatter over the greens of the spring onion for garnish.